		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Passive optical network</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox ambox-content" style="">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div style="width: 52px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="image" title="Question book-new.svg"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" width="50" height="39" border="0" /></a></div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text" style="">This article <b>does not <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" title="Wikipedia:Citing sources">cite</a> any <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">references or sources</a></b>. Please help <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Passive_optical_network&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Passive_optical_network&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow">improve this article</a> by adding citations to <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Reliable_sources" title="Wikipedia:Reliable sources">reliable sources</a> (ideally, using <i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes" title="Wikipedia:Footnotes">inline citations</a></i>). Unsourced material may be <a href="/wiki/Template:Fact" title="Template:Fact">challenged</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BURDEN" title="Wikipedia:BURDEN" class="mw-redirect">removed</a>. <small><i>(May 2007)</i></small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>A <b>passive optical network</b> (<b>PON</b>) is a <a href="/wiki/Point-to-multipoint" title="Point-to-multipoint" class="mw-redirect">point-to-multipoint</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fiber_to_the_premises" title="Fiber to the premises" class="mw-redirect">fiber to the premises</a> network architecture in which unpowered <a href="/wiki/Optical_splitter" title="Optical splitter" class="mw-redirect">optical splitters</a> are used to enable a single <a href="/wiki/Optical_fiber" title="Optical fiber">optical fiber</a> to serve multiple premises, typically 32-128. A PON consists of an <a href="/w/index.php?title=Optical_Line_Terminal&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Optical Line Terminal (page does not exist)">Optical Line Terminal</a> (OLT) at the service provider's central office and a number of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Optical_Network_Unit&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Optical Network Unit (page does not exist)">Optical Network Units</a> (ONUs) near end users. A PON configuration reduces the amount of fiber and central office equipment required compared with <a href="/wiki/Network_topology#Point-to-point" title="Network topology">point to point</a> architectures.</p>
<p>Downstream signals are broadcast to each premises sharing a fiber. <a href="/wiki/Encryption" title="Encryption">Encryption</a> is used to prevent <a href="/wiki/Eavesdropping" title="Eavesdropping">eavesdropping</a>.</p>
<p>Upstream signals are combined using a <a href="/wiki/Multiple_access" title="Multiple access" class="mw-redirect">multiple access</a> protocol, invariably <a href="/wiki/Time_division_multiple_access" title="Time division multiple access">time division multiple access</a> (TDMA). The OLTs "range" the ONUs in order to provide time slot assignments for upstream communication.</p>
